bastln mitochondrial genes against their contigs

I have two main questions I am working through right now:

  1. How do I select which genes to annotate
  2. Why are there so many ND# mt genes with issues?

Exploratory analysis of blastn data

Here we have blasted (tblstn) translated AA mtDNA genes identified with mitofinder against the UCE contigs they were found in. About half of the assembled contigs threw a warning from mitofinder, indicating they might be contaminated, fragmented, or NUMTS are present and need to be checked. I’ve already checked for contamination and identified a couple samples to remove. The aim now is to find which contigs we should analyize for NUMTs and fragmentation. I added two additional columns with the sample name_id and gene at the end of the dataframe before importing the dataframe

dependant packages

library(readr)

Take into account percentage of identity and length

Lets look at the percentage of identity times the length of the match; and then plot that against the bitscore.

plot(d$pident * d$length, d$bitscore, xaxt = "n", yaxt="n", xlab="",ylab="")
  axis(1, xaxp=c(0,50000, 25), las=1, font=2, cex.axis=0.8)
  axis(2, font=2, cex.axis=0.8)
#mtext(side = 1, line=1, "Percentage of Identity x Length", font=2, cex=1.2)
title(main="All blastn results",cex.lab=1.2)
title(ylab="bitscore",
      xlab="Percentage of Identity x Length",
      cex.lab=1.2, line =2.5)

This makes sense, the longer the tblastn match, the more confident we are about the match.

plot all alle genes this way

genes<-unique(d$gene)
                   
for(i in genes){
  length <- d %>% filter(gene==i) %>% nrow()
  n <- d %>% filter(gene==i) %>% distinct(id) %>% nrow()
  list1 <- d %>% filter(gene==i) %>% 
    ggplot(., aes(x= pident, y=bitscore)) +
    geom_point(size=2, stroke=1.3, 
               aes(shape=id,color=id)) +
    scale_shape_manual(values=1:n) +
    scale_color_manual(values=1:n) +
    theme(legend.title = element_blank(), legend.text=element_text(size=8),
          legend.position="bottom") +
    ggtitle(paste("Prob. Ident. x Bitscore;",i,"n =",n))
  print(list1)
}

subset a sample

Whats up with the ND# genes?

Over half of the genes with issues are ND# genes. Is this an artifact sequencing, assembly, or biologically relevent?

d %>% filter(grepl("ND",gene)) %>% nrow() / d %>%  nrow()
## [1] 0.5759535

We can see that over half of our blast matches are represented by one of the ND# genes…

d.ND <- d %>% filter(grepl("ND",gene))

Is it reasonable to create a new column that gives us a ratio = (pidnt*length) / bitscore and exclude anything outside of a lower 95% confidence interval?

pident_length <- (d.ND$pident*d.ND$length)/d.ND$bitscore
hist(pident_length, prob=T,  ylim=c(0,0.04),xlim=c(0,300))
lines(density(pident_length, adjust=3))

all <- d %>% filter(!grepl("ND",gene)) %>% select(pident, length, bitscore)
pident_length.all <- (all$pident*all$length)/all$bitscore
hist(pident_length.all, prob=T,  ylim=c(0,0.05), xlim=c(0,300))
lines(density(pident_length.all, adjust=3))

ND% genes dont seem to behave too differently from other samples, this may kick some samples, but that is OK for now maybe. This is probably the biggest issue with the mitochondrial analyses. I already have identified 1-2 samples that will have to be removed anyways.

Adding the ratio that’s been calculated using dplyr::mutate

d2 <- d %>% mutate(ratio = (pident*length)/bitscore)

for(i in genes){
  list2 <- d2 %>% filter (gene==i) %>% 
    ggplot(., aes(x = ratio)) +
    geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), colour="black", fill="white") +
    geom_density(alpha=.2, fill="#FF6666") +
    ggtitle(paste("mt-tblastn gene",i))
  print(list2)
}
